## Known Limitations

**CREME-MC comparison shoulder -- RESOLVED 2026-07-19, was a methodology bug** (see `compare_creme_panda.py`, `Documentation/PANDA_VALIDATION_SUMMARY.md` Section 1.3, README "Known limitations"):

The gap previously reported here (PANDA's cross-section curve sitting roughly 1-2 orders of magnitude above CREME-MC's in the ~2-20 fC range, log-RMSE ~0.9 decades) was traced to `compare_creme_panda.py` comparing CREME-MC's ideal-100%-charge-collection reference (the RPP model's convention, shared by CUPID) against PANDA's **collected**-charge cross section, which additionally applies PANDA's own drift/trapping collection-efficiency model (`Qeff = T*Qgen`, T<1). The two curves were never directly comparable quantities.

Fixed by comparing against PANDA's **deposited**-charge cross section instead (PANDA's 100%-collection-equivalent output). Corrected result: log-RMSE ~0.29 decades across the full curve (all 50/50 digitized CREME-MC points within PANDA's simulated range) -- the curves visually overlap almost entirely, including through the ~3-10 fC region previously described as an unexplained intermediate-charge "hump."

The previous root-cause narrative (different nuclear reaction model families -- Geant4's cascade/pre-compound physics vs. CREME-MC's semi-empirical fragmentation cross-sections, citing published Geant4-vs-CREME96 comparisons at [arXiv:0712.2149](https://arxiv.org/pdf/0712.2149)) does not hold up once the comparison uses the correct quantity. That literature may still be relevant to genuinely different discrepancies elsewhere, but is no longer needed to explain this one. No longer treated as an expected, unfixable disagreement.

**McNulty et al. comparison under-prediction** (see `compare_mcnulty_panda.py`, README "Known limitations"):

Compared against McNulty et al.'s 148 MeV proton-induced integral cross-section-vs-deposited-energy data (measured and CUPID simulation, digitized from a McNulty-authored review reproduced in DTIC report AD-A285581), using PANDA configured to the same 11.7x11.7x13.5 um silicon sensitive volume.

Original run (vacuum world, no secondary-neutron biasing): PANDA systematically under-predicted, growing smoothly from ~1.4x at 1 MeV deposited to >100x by 25-28 MeV (log-RMSE ~1.1 decades vs. the experimental curve).

Root cause: PANDA's sensitive+dead-layer stack sat in a vacuum world (`G4_Galactic`), with no material outside it for a nearby nuclear reaction to occur in. McNulty's CUPID model explicitly included a silicon "surrounding volume" -- this is the actual subject of the 1989 paper this comparison was originally aimed at (El-Teleaty, McNulty, Abdel-Kader, Beauvais, "Soft Fails in Microelectronic Circuits Due to Proton-Induced Nuclear Reactions in Material Surrounding the SEU-Sensitive Volume," Nucl. Instr. and Meth. B40/41, 1300-1305 (1989); that paper's own data table wasn't accessible, hence using the closely related digitized figure instead). The discrepancy growing with deposited energy, rather than being flat across the range, was consistent with surrounding-volume-sourced recoils being the missing contribution.

Addressed (partially) via the Surrounding Volume + Secondary-Neutron Biasing exception (Section 5): adding a 100 um silicon surrounding volume plus biasing secondary neutrons within it (silicon's cm-scale neutron mean free path meant unbiased secondary neutrons almost never reacted again within any practically-sized volume) improved the log-RMSE to ~0.91 decades vs. the experimental curve -- roughly an 18% reduction. (Note: this used to be described as "in the same ballpark as the CREME-MC discrepancy above" -- that comparison point is now stale, since the CREME-MC gap above turned out to be a fixed methodology bug rather than a real ~0.9-decade discrepancy; McNulty's ~0.91-decade residual is the larger of the two now.) Per-energy improvement is real but uneven: e.g. the 10 MeV discrepancy dropped from 3.07x to 2.47x, but the 25 MeV discrepancy only dropped from ~133x to ~48x -- still a large gap.

**Remaining gap -- RESOLVED-BY-REFRAMING 2026-07-19: expected/structural, not an open problem.** Two of the plausible contributing factors listed here were directly tested:

- **Beam footprint tied to sensitiveXY (11.7 um), not the surrounding volume (100 um)**: reran with `beamXY` widened to 100 um. Result: log-RMSE went from 0.426 to 0.455 decades (over a matched energy range) -- slightly *worse*, not better. Ruled out.
- **100 um surrounding volume too small**: reran at 300 um and 500 um surrounding volume. Result: log-RMSE was flat (0.900 -> 0.887 -> 0.945 decades), no improving trend. Ruled out.

**Why neither helped, physically** (Mark's explanation, a firsthand participant in the original McNulty-era experimental work): secondaries generated far from the sensitive volume are predominantly light, weakly-ionizing particles (e.g. neutrons) -- they travel far but deposit little energy directly. The particles that would deposit meaningful energy -- heavy recoil fragments -- have very short range precisely because they lose energy so quickly. Only a reaction happening close to the sensitive volume can produce a heavy fragment that actually reaches it, so growing the shell (or widening the beam to sample more of it) adds volume that can't contribute either way. This is a structural feature of the physics, not a fixable sampling gap -- consistent with silicon's cm-scale neutron mean free path meaning even 500 um is a small fraction of it, but explaining *why* that length-scale mismatch matters rather than just noting it.

Two candidates remain formally untested (only one cascade generation biased; other secondary species not biased), but given the mechanism above, further chasing this gap has a low expected return.

**On what "agreement" should mean here**: PANDA (Geant4 cascade/pre-compound physics) and CUPID (liquid-drop nuclear model) are fundamentally different nuclear models, not two numerical approximations of the same one -- "trying to get an exact match between an apple (geant4-libraries) and an orange (liquid drop model of the nucleus)" (Mark). The original McNulty research team has also largely left the field, so there is no one left to consult for further clarification on that 1989/1991-era work beyond what's already published. Judged by the standard actually used for cross-code nuclear-model validation elsewhere in the field (e.g. MCNP-style comparisons), agreement within an order of magnitude with closely-matching curve shape between two fundamentally different models **is** a genuine validation, not a residual defect awaiting a fix.

